{
  "answer": "In Cynewulf's *Andreas*, Matthew invokes Christ as \"Savior of souls\" (*Hælend*) during his imprisonment among cannibals, emphasizing his role as deliverer from both immediate physical peril (imminent devouring) and eternal damnation.[^1]\n\nIn the same poem, Andreas rebukes the disguised Christ (as helmsman) by citing \"Christ Himself\" (*Crist*) as \"the glorious King\" who commands apostolic missions without worldly provisions, highlighting his messianic authority and divine kingship as teacher and ruler of creation.[^2]\n\nAt the poem's outset, the apostles are styled \"the Lord’s own champions\" (*Dryhten*), underscoring Christ's sovereign lordship as Heaven's High King who ordains human fates in battle, akin to a heroic overlord allotting doom and glory.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-26403d).\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-355089).\n[^3]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-868413).",
